text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!MorphosyntacticDiversity]]%0a%0a!Multiple Modals%0a%0a:Author: EthanW%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aMore than one modal (can, will, should) occuring in a single sentence%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aModal verbs, such as "can", "may" and "shall", always accompany the base form of another verb to express modality like possibility, permission, and obligation, etc. In Standardized American English, no more than one modal verb can appear before the base verb, so for example the sentence 1b shown below is ungrammatical: %0a1a. I can swim. %0a1b. *I must can swim. %0a%0aHowever, in South Midland and Southern American varieties of English multiple modals are widely attested. There are several observed combinations. Sometimes multiple modals contain a modal and a quasimodal ("better", "need to", "supposed to", etc.), though this is not always the case. Usually, multiple modals have "might" or "may" as their first modal, and the most commonly used expressions include "might could", "might can" and "might would". Nonetheless, there are also examples like "could might". Finally, it is possible to have more than two modals, as in setence 2c, so we use the name "multiple" instead of "double". %0a%0aHere is a list of some example sentences with multiple modals: %0a2a. I was afraid you might couldn't find it. %0a2b. How could you might do that? %0a2c. It's a long way and he might will can't come. %0a%0aReferences: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modal_verb; https://ygdp.yale.edu/phenomena/multiple-modals%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210424-180331-127510#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Multiple modals in media %0a-> - ZoeC%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%0aThere are additional examples of multiple modals in books and other media. For example, here is a multiple modal moment in Walter Mosley’s Devil in a Blue Dress: “Don’t get me wrong, Ease. DeWitt is a tough man, and he runs in bad company. But you still might could get that mortgage payment an’ you might even learn sumpin’ from’im.”%0a%0aAnother example is from the American television show, Deadwater, which is about a post-civil war mining town. Here is a line from that show:%0a“if her wounds don't fester she might can have a fighting chance”%0a%0aMultiple modals are often used in southern U.S. dialects like in this example, but can also be used in Scottish English. In the Scots Syntax Atlas, there is a video of a Scottish speaker from Selkirk saying the sentence, ”Some people might can”. The link to this video along with the other references is below.%0a %0ahttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ojQ_poNaoJc&t=19s%0ahttps://stancarey.wordpress.com/2012/02/06/you-might-could-dig-these-multiple-modals/%0ahttps://ygdp.yale.edu/phenomena/multiple-modals%0a%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210424-180331-127510#%0a#foxbegin 210425-034628-598950#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Multiple Modals in Mandarin %0a-> - EthanR%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aMultiple modals also exist in Mandarin!%0a%0a李医生   明天       可能  做    午饭%0aDr. Li  tomorrow  may  cook  lunch%0a%0a王老师   明天       可能  会   做    午饭%0aDr. Li  tomorrow  may  will cook  lunch%0a%0aBoth have the same meaning of 'Dr. Li may cook lunch tomorrow'%0a%0aSource: https://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download?doi=10.1.1.541.5985&rep=rep1&type=pdf%0a%0a(apologies for any errors in translations! 我需要多学中文！) %0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210425-034628-598950#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: E:)%0a(:Category: MorphosyntacticDiversity:)
